'''''101 Zen Stories''''' is a 1919 compilation of [[Zen]] [[koan]]s<ref name="zensite">{{cite web|title=Koan Studies|url=http://www.thezensite.com/MainPages/koan_studies.html|publisher=thezensite|accessdate=April 24, 2013}}</ref> including 19th and early 20th century [[anecdote]]s compiled by [[Nyogen Senzaki]],<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Nancy Wilson|title=The World of Zen: An East-West Anthology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MILXAAAAMAAJ&q=%22101+Zen+Stories%22&dq=%22101+Zen+Stories%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8fWBT6mdHYSi8gS9rvW7Bw&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBQ|page=xxii|publisher=Vintage|isbn=9780394703015}}</ref> and a translation of ''[[Shasekishū]]'',<ref name="zensite"/><ref name="bones">{{cite book|last1=Reps|first1=Paul|last2=Senzaki|first2=Nyogen|authorlink1=Paul Reps|authorlink2=Nyogen Senzaki|title=[[Zen Flesh, Zen Bones]]: A Collection of Zen and Pre-zen Writings|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|page=17|isbn=9780804831864}}</ref> written in the 13th century by [[Japan]]ese Zen master [[Mujū]] (無住) (literally, "non-dweller").<ref name="bones"/> The book was reprinted by [[Paul Reps]] as part of ''Zen Flesh, Zen Bones''.<ref>{{cite book|last=Ross|first=Nancy Wilson|title=The World of Zen: An East-West Anthology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MILXAAAAMAAJ&q=%22101+Zen+Stories%22&dq=%22101+Zen+Stories%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=8fWBT6mdHYSi8gS9rvW7Bw&ved=0CE8Q6AEwBQ|page= 74|publisher=Vintage|isbn=9780394703015}}</ref><ref name="bones"/> Well-known koans in the collection include ''A Cup of Tea'' (1), ''The Sound of One Hand'' (21), ''No Water, No Moon'' (29), and ''Everything is Best'' (31).

