'''Anukul Chandra Mukerji'''  (1888–1968) was an Indian academic, thinker, writer and the professor of philosophy at [[Allahabad University]].<ref name="Anukul Chandra Mukerji: The Modern Subject">{{cite journal | url=http://www.oxfordhandbooks.com/view/10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199314621.001.0001/oxfordhb-9780199314621-e-42 | title=Anukul Chandra Mukerji: The Modern Subject | author=Nalini Bhushan, Jay L. Garfield | journal=The Oxford Handbook of Indian Philosophy | year=July 2015 | doi=10.1093/oxfordhb/9780199314621.013.42}}</ref> He was known for his studies on the philosophy of European thinkers such as [[Immanuel Kant]] and [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel]], psychologists like [[William James]], [[John B. Watson]], and [[James Ward (psychologist)|James Ward]] as well as the [[Advaita Vedanta]] of [[Adi Shankara]]. He was the author two notable books, ''Self, Thought, and Reality''<ref name="Self, Thought, and Reality">{{cite book | url=http://journals.cambridge.org/action/displayAbstract?fromPage=online&aid=3490984&fileId=S0031819100033350 | title=Self, Thought, and Reality | publisher=Juvenile Press | author=A. C. Mukherjee | year=1933 | pages=410 | DOI=10.1017/S0031819100033350}}</ref> and ''The Nature of Self''<ref name="The Nature of Self">{{cite book | url=https://www.researchgate.net/publication/231937065_The_Nature_of_Self_By_A_C_Mukerji_MA_Reader_in_Philosophy_Allahabad_University_Allahabad_The_Indian_Press_1938_Pp_xii359_Price_Rs_5 | title=The Nature of Self | publisher=The Indian Press | author=A. C. Mukherjee | year=1938 | pages=359 | DOI=10.1017/S0031819100036032}}</ref> and several articles<ref name="Indian Philosophy in English: From Renaissance to Independence">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=cxdwAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA323&lpg=PA323&dq=Anukul+Chandra+Mukherjee&source=bl&ots=8wlExg8tic&sig=Kq9jIat3HxH5bW4EBBJ0CQ79VkY&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX8oLd38LLAhWLsxQKHdCdAx44ChDoAQgzMAY#v=onepage&q=Anukul%20Chandra%20Mukherjee&f=false | title=Indian Philosophy in English: From Renaissance to Independence | publisher=Google Books | date=2016 | accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> and is known to have employed western methodology and language styles in his academic pursuit.<ref name="Migrating Texts and Traditions">{{cite book | url=https://books.google.ae/books?id=hppjAwAAQBAJ&pg=PT102&lpg=PT102&dq=Anukul+Chandra+Mukherjee&source=bl&ots=lgcXtuagEt&sig=GrFnPcx3f6akPuqj5fLrmxHZVdo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjX8oLd38LLAhWLsxQKHdCdAx44ChDoAQg6MAg#v=onepage&q=Anukul%20Chandra%20Mukherjee&f=false | title=Migrating Texts and Traditions | publisher=University of Ottawa Press | author=William Sweet (Editor) | year=2012 | pages=364 | isbn=9780776620329}}</ref> The Government of India awarded him the third highest civilian honour of the [[Padma Bhushan]], in 1964, for his contributions to education and literature.<ref name="Padma Awards">{{cite web|url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |title=Padma Awards |publisher=Ministry of Home Affairs, Government of India |date=2016 |accessdate=3 January 2016 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6U68ulwpb?url=http://mha.nic.in/sites/upload_files/mha/files/LST-PDAWD-2013.pdf |archivedate=15 November 2014 |df= }}</ref>

