'''Endurantism''' or '''endurance theory''' is a philosophical theory of persistence and [[Identity (philosophy)|identity]]. According to the endurantist view, material objects are persisting three-dimensional individuals wholly present at every moment of their existence, which goes with an [[A-theory of time]]. This conception of an individual as always present is opposed to [[perdurantism]] or [[four dimensionalism]], which maintains that an object is a series of [[temporal parts]] or stages, requiring a [[B-theory of time]]. The use of "endure" and "perdure" to distinguish two ways in which an object can be thought to persist can be traced to [[David Lewis (philosopher)|David Lewis]].
