'''''The Theory of Good and Evil''''' is a 1907 book about [[ethics]] by the English philosopher [[Hastings Rashdall]]. It has been seen as Rashdall's most important philosophical work. Rashdall's work has been compared to that of the philosopher [[G. E. Moore]].

==Summary==
{{expand section|date=November 2018}}
''The Theory of Good and Evil'' is dedicated to the philosophers [[Thomas Hill Green]] and [[Henry Sidgwick]]. In the work, Rashdall discusses ethics. Subjects addressed include [[utilitarianism]], the work of the philosopher [[G. E. Moore]], including ''[[Principia Ethica]]'' (1903), the work of [[F. H. Bradley]], and [[Christian theology]].{{sfn|Rashdall|2004|pages=v–vii}} In his second volume, he deals with potential objections to his views.{{sfn|Rashdall|2004|pages=iii, 1, 83, 287, 311}}

==Publication history==
''The Theory of Good and Evil'' was first published by the [[Clarendon Press]] in 1907. In 2004, it was republished by Elibron Classics.{{sfn|Rashdall|2004|page=ii}}

==Reception==
===Academic journals===
''The Theory of Good and Evil'' was discussed by Daniel Shannon in ''Saint Anselm Journal''. Shannon described the book as Rashdall's best known work, but criticized Rashdall's evaluation of Christian theology.{{sfn|Shannon|2009|pages=1–19}}

===Evaluations in books===
The philosopher [[Richard Wollheim]] described ''The Theory of Good and Evil'' as "a compendious work marred by priggishness" in ''F. H. Bradley'' (1969).{{sfn|Wollheim|1969|page=271}} The philosopher [[John Rawls]] compared Rashdall's ethical views to those of Moore, writing in ''[[A Theory of Justice]]'' (1971) that the position that the capacity for a higher life may be grounds for treating men unequally is implicit in ''Principia Ethica''.{{sfn|Rawls|1999|page=287}} James W. Allard described ''The Theory of Good and Evil'' as Rashdall's most important philosophical work in ''[[The Cambridge Dictionary of Philosophy]]'' (1999).{{sfn|Allard|1999|page=771}} R. S. Downie considered Rashdall's dedication of ''The Theory of Good and Evil'' to Green and Sidgwick appropriate, noting in ''[[The Oxford Companion to Philosophy]]'' (2005) that Rashdall was indebted to both philosophers. He suggested that Rashdall had been "unfairly eclipsed as a moral philosopher" by Moore.{{sfn|Downie|2005|page=782}}

